 (151,1,'2016-05-09 04:55:17','2016-05-09 04:55:17','Authors: <a href=\"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/search/searchresult.jsp?searchWithin=%22Authors%22:.QT.N.%20R.%20W.%20W.%20M.%20R.%20D%20Wickramasingha.QT.&amp;newsearch=true\">R. W. W. M. R. D Wickramasingha</a> ; Department of Computer Engineering, University of Peradeniya, Sri Lanka ; <a href=\"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/search/searchresult.jsp?searchWithin=%22Authors%22:.QT.H.%20B.%20R.%20A.%20K.%20R.%20A.%20M%20Keerawella.QT.&amp;newsearch=true\">H. B. R. A. K. R. A. M Keerawella</a> ; <a href=\"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/search/searchresult.jsp?searchWithin=%22Authors%22:.QT.S.%20A.%20N%20Samarasinghe.QT.&amp;newsearch=true\">S. A. N Samarasinghe</a> ; <a href=\"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/search/searchresult.jsp?searchWithin=%22Authors%22:.QT.R.%20G.%20Ragel.QT.&amp;newsearch=true\">R. G. Ragel</a>\r\n\r\nCompletely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart (CAPTCHA) is a challenge-response system test used on the web, designed to differentiate humans from automated computer systems. Most of the widely used CAPTCHA systems are designed with desktop users in mind hence lack the native look and feel when they are used on mobile devices. The reason is the way people interact with desktop/laptop computer using mouse and keyboard is different from the way they interact with mobile devices using touch and other gestures. Also, the screen size and the dimension of the viewing display plays a role in the interaction. Here, we present a novel CAPTCHA system designed for mobile devices and results of the usability study that we conducted with an implementation of the same. This CAPTCHA system is composed of multipart image reconstruction and orientation identification. Although, this is an intuitive task for humans, it is very hard to automate using a computer system. The main advantages of our system over traditional systems are native mobile look and feel, language/culture independent, and gesture-based interaction.\r\n\r\n<strong>Published in: </strong><a href=\"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/mostRecentIssue.jsp?punumber=7391617\">2015 IEEE 10th International Conference on Industrial and Information Systems (ICIIS)</a>\r\n\r\n<strong> IEEE Xplore link:<u>  </u></strong><a href=\"http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/articleDetails.jsp?arnumber=7398984&amp;queryText=iciis%202015&amp;refinements=4224982482&amp;refinements=4224981563&amp;refinements=4224982573&amp;refinements=4224983845\">http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/articleDetails.jsp?arnumber=7398984&amp;queryText=iciis%202015&amp;refinements=4224982482&amp;refinements=4224981563&amp;refinements=4224982573&amp;refinements=4224983845</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','RotateCAPTCHA a novel interactive CAPTCHA design targeting mobile devices','','inherit','closed','closed','','150-revision-v1','','','2016-05-09 04:55:17','2016-05-09 04:55:17','',150,'http://localhost/ieeeuop/2016/05/09/150-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
 (152,1,'2016-05-09 05:09:32','2016-05-09 05:09:32','Article By: Naveena Amandani Jayarathne\r\nDepartment of Electrical and Electronic Engineering\r\n<h3><strong>Acoustical Engineering</strong></h3>\r\nOne can interpret Audio Engineering as the involvement of Engineering in Music. In other words, audio engineering is a discipline of engineering that deals with the technical aspects of sound during recording and reproduction. The name itself suggests that this discipline of Engineering greatly deals with “sound” which is fundamentally, the birth of music. The Oxford English Dictionary defines “Audio” as “sound, especially when recorded, transmitted or reproduced”. Audio Engineering is one of the few key ingredients in the production of good music. People who work to ensure that the music we hear when artists perform during recordings arein good condition are called Audio or Sound Engineers. In other words, an Audio Engineer is someone, who is highly concerned about recording, mixing, manipulation and reproduction of sound. The fine music that we hear at a live concert or on a CD is a result of all the hard work of a skillful sound engineer. Audio Engineering, which is also known as Sound Engineering or Acoustical Engineering leads to a career which is all about capturing, recording, mixing, editing and reproducing sound with the help of technology. This technology is based on mechanical and electronic instruments and devices designed to filter and mix audio signals. One might think that this discipline of Engineering only requires expertise in Electronics and IT. But, the reality is that this field of engineering requires expertise from many areas of study such as music, acoustics and electronics plus the basic knowledge in physics. It’s equally important to have a sound understanding about computers and software since the most of it is processed by computers nowadays. As almost all the post-production tasks are handled by computer software, an audio engineer must be proficient in handling a computer.\r\n\r\nIf it wasn’t for Thomas Edison’s Gramophone in 1877, we would not have achieved all of this ‘magic’ in acoustical engineering so fast, along with the enhancement and rapid development of electronics technology and computer science. Today, music plays a major role in our lives with all these iPods, MP3 players plus all the other media players and phones well equipped with all sorts of music.A sound engineer must be very sharp and keen to record even the slightest and the most delicate sound variations. That is how you can preserve the quality of the output. Not only capturing the audio signal would take care of the quality of the processed or the reconstructed signal, but also the equipment and accessories that are being used in the process. For example,top quality recording studios use a special type of cables which are capable of transmitting audio signals with the minimum noise in them.\r\n\r\nOther than the tech aspects, the workspace of a sound engineer defines a few other sub disciplines of sound engineering. The following sub disciplines are based on PACS(Physics and Astronomy Classification Scheme) coding used by the Acoustical Society of America. However many of us do not understand that that capturing a good sound within a room is a science, a science in which an audio engineer plays the main role. This science and engineering is called <strong>Architectural Acoustics</strong>. Audio Engineers develop algorithms to allow electronic manipulation of audio signals. The algorithms may carry out echo cancellation on Skype or other video/audio transmitting software. <strong>Electro acoustics</strong> is concerned with the design of headphones, microphones, loudspeakers, sound reproduction systems and recording technologies. <strong>Psychoacoustics </strong>is the scientific study of how humans respond to what they hear. <strong>Musical acoustics</strong> is concerned with researching and describing the science of music. In audio engineering, this includes the design of electronic instruments such as synthesizers. Depending on the area of specialization, the working environment (also called the workspace) of an audio engineer can change. It can range from an institution of higher education to film studios. Most common workspaces of an audio engineer are music studios, film studios, television studios, opera houses, play houses, theatres, conference centres, auditoriums etc.\r\n\r\nThe picture that flashes on to our minds as soon as we hear the word “Sound Engineering” is a person operating an electronic panel with a number of blinking lights, switches, dials and meters on it. This board is called the “Electronic Mixing Board” which is also considered to be the heart of sound processing during post production. The process of post-production includes refurbishing the final output. The recorded sound is made even better and much flawless at this stage. An audio engineer deals with a number of several other electronic devices other than the mixing board such as, amplifiers, ADC(Analog to Digital Converters), DAC(Digital to Analog Converters), DAW(Digital Audio Workstations), Signal Processors, Tape Machines, Pre-Amplifiers, Music Sequencers, Mixing Consoles, Microphones, Loudspeakers etc.\r\n\r\nThe career of an audio engineer can come along several different paths, depending on the sub-field that they are interested in. Some of the sub fields are recording, DVD production, post production, record labels, forensic audio, music restoration/preservation and internet audio broadcast etc. An audio engineer is given different specific names depending on the service he/she provides.\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>Studio Engineer</strong>\r\nA studio engineer works closely with producers in a studio. Sometimes studio engineers double as the producer and work independently.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Assistant Engineer</strong>\r\nAn assistant engineer usually works in a studio setting as well. They are often apprentices to studio engineers who own or work in large facilities.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Recording Engineer</strong>\r\nA recording engineer is someone who focuses specifically on the aspect of recording sound.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Game &amp; Audio Design Engineer</strong>\r\nA game &amp; audio design engineer helps work with the sound engineering on video games, as well as how to appropriately add sound to the game.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Mix Engineer</strong>\r\nA mix engineer focuses on mixing together different tracks to mesh and create a new track.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Mastering Engineer</strong>\r\nA mastering engineer smoothens over the results of a mix engineer, making the final product into a whole.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Live Sound Engineer</strong>\r\nA live sound engineer works at live events to make sure the sound is of appropriate value and high quality.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Monitor Engineer</strong>\r\nA monitor engineer works with live sound engineers to help the performers at a live event hear themselves.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Systems Engineer</strong>\r\nA systems engineer manages the entire experience of sound at live performances. Systems engineers manage both live sound engineers and monitor engineers, and also work to set up the entire live sound system at many live events.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Audio Post Engineer</strong>\r\nAn audio post engineer works to mix and edit audio for television and movies.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class=\" wp-image-154 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost/ieeeuop/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/naveena-300x208.jpg\" alt=\"naveena\" width=\"434\" height=\"301\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFurthermore, Audio Engineering is more known to be a career which comprises the practical aspects of music as much as the theories in music. Development of technology solved most of the difficulties faced by artists and sound engineers during live recordings. They can now make better recordings without having to repeat the same performance, all thanks to the high end computer software and electronic equipment. A skillful sound engineer is capable of doing fine make-overs with the available cutting edge technology leaving only the slightest trace of reproduction of the original. Using tomorrow\'s technology, our children and grandchildren may find it difficult to distinguish the real thing from the reproduced.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-155\" src=\"http://localhost/ieeeuop/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/AAEAAQAAAAAAAAUGAAAAJDEyM2FlYTcyLTA5OGQtNDFmOS1iZmI3LWIyOTNkNTc0ZWRjMQ-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"AAEAAQAAAAAAAAUGAAAAJDEyM2FlYTcyLTA5OGQtNDFmOS1iZmI3LWIyOTNkNTc0ZWRjMQ\" width=\"80\" height=\"80\" />\r\nNaveena Amandani Jayarathne\r\nLinkedIn: <a href=\"https://lk.linkedin.com/in/naveena-jayarathne-b93106108\">https://lk.linkedin.com/in/naveena-jayarathne-b93106108</a>','AUDIO ENGINEERING','','publish','open','open','','audio-engineering','','','2016-05-09 08:44:13','2016-05-09 08:44:13','',0,'http://localhost/ieeeuop/?p=152',0,'post','',0);
